---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import PageHero from '../../components/ui/PageHero.astro';
import GuideShell from '../../components/guides/GuideShell.astro';
import ChatMock from '../../components/guides/ChatMock.astro';
import DashFrame from '../../components/guides/DashFrame.astro';

const sections = [
    { id: 'connect', heading: 'Connect your channel', note: 'One Twitch sign-in. No API keys, no config files, nothing to install.' },
    { id: 'tour', heading: 'Find your way around', note: 'Five places in the sidebar. You will spend most of your time in two of them.' },
    { id: 'first-command', heading: 'Create your first command', note: 'A name and a response. Everything else is optional.' },
    { id: 'first-module', heading: 'Switch on your first module', note: 'Modules are bigger features with an on/off switch. Two are already on for you.' },
    { id: 'go-live', heading: 'Go live with confidence', note: 'A two-minute pre-stream checklist, then the bot takes the night shift.' },
];
---

<Layout
    title="Getting started — ItsBagelBot Guides"
    description="Set up ItsBagelBot in minutes: connect your Twitch channel, tour the dashboard, create your first command, and switch on your first module."
    ogType="article"
>
    <PageHero
        eyebrow="Guide 01"
        title="Getting started"
        description="From “Add to Twitch” to your first stream with the bot in chat. Ten minutes, start to finish, most of it reading."
    />

    <GuideShell
        sections={sections}
        minutes="6 min read"
        next={{ href: '/guides/commands', label: 'Commands & variables' }}
    >
        <Fragment slot="connect">
            <p>
                Head to <a href="https://dashboard.itsbagelbot.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">dashboard.itsbagelbot.com</a>
                and sign in with your Twitch account. Twitch shows you exactly what the bot is allowed
                to do before you approve anything, and that's the whole setup. The moment you're in,
                ItsBagelBot joins your chat and sits quietly until it's spoken to.
            </p>
            <ChatMock
                title="#your_channel"
                caption="What your chat sees, about two seconds after you sign in."
                lines={[
                    { who: 'system', text: 'itsbagelbot joined #your_channel' },
                    { who: 'viewer', name: 'maya_live', text: 'oh a new bot, hi!' },
                ]}
            />
            <p class="gtip">
                <b>Good to know</b>
                The bot never speaks unprompted. Until you create commands or enable modules, joining
                is the only thing it does: your chat stays exactly as it was.
            </p>
        </Fragment>

        <Fragment slot="tour">
            <p>
                The dashboard is one sidebar with five stops. <strong>Overview</strong> is your landing
                page, <strong>Commands</strong> is where custom chat commands live, and
                <strong>Modules</strong> holds every bigger feature. Billing and Settings do what they
                say on the tin.
            </p>
            <DashFrame
                path="/"
                caption="The dashboard, annotated."
                notes={[
                    { n: 1, text: 'Commands: create and edit the !commands your viewers type. The next section starts here.' },
                    { n: 2, text: 'Modules: alerts, timers, loyalty points, game stats… each with a single on/off switch.' },
                    { n: 3, text: "Your channel's status at a glance: what's enabled and whether the bot is in chat." },
                ]}
            >
                <div class="df-app">
                    <div class="df-side">
                        <span class="is-active">Overview</span>
                        <span>Commands <i class="df-dot" style="position:static; width:16px; height:16px; font-size:0.55rem; margin-left:4px;">1</i></span>
                        <span>Modules <i class="df-dot" style="position:static; width:16px; height:16px; font-size:0.55rem; margin-left:4px;">2</i></span>
                        <span>Billing</span>
                        <span>Settings</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="df-main">
                        <p class="df-title">Overview</p>
                        <div class="df-row"><span class="df-grow">Bot connected to #your_channel</span><span class="df-pill df-pill--on">in chat</span><i class="df-dot" style="position:static;">3</i></div>
                        <div class="df-row"><span class="df-grow">Chat Alerts</span><span class="df-pill df-pill--on">on</span></div>
                        <div class="df-row"><span class="df-grow">AutoMod</span><span class="df-pill df-pill--on">on</span></div>
                        <div class="df-row"><span class="df-grow">Timers</span><span class="df-pill df-pill--off">off</span></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </DashFrame>
            <p>
                Everything on the dashboard saves the moment you confirm it: there's no "deploy" step,
                and changes reach your chat within seconds.
            </p>
        </Fragment>

        <Fragment slot="first-command">
            <p>
                Open <strong>Commands</strong> and press <strong>New command</strong>. A command needs
                exactly two things: a <strong>name</strong> (what viewers type after the
                <code>!</code>) and a <strong>response</strong> (what the bot says back). Let's make
                the classic:
            </p>
            <DashFrame
                path="/commands"
                caption="The command editor with just the two required fields filled in."
                notes={[
                    { n: 1, text: 'The name, without the “!” (the dashboard adds it in chat). Lowercase, no spaces.' },
                    { n: 2, text: 'The response. Plain text is fine; the next guide shows the variables that make it smart.' },
                    { n: 3, text: 'Create saves it instantly. The command works in chat from this moment.' },
                ]}
            >
                <div class="df-main">
                    <p class="df-title">New command</p>
                    <div class="df-field"><span>Name</span><div class="df-input is-focus">discord<i class="df-dot" style="position:static; margin-left:auto;">1</i></div></div>
                    <div class="df-field"><span>Response</span><div class="df-input">Come hang out between streams → discord.gg/your-invite<i class="df-dot" style="position:static; margin-left:auto;">2</i></div></div>
                    <div class="df-actions"><span class="df-btn df-btn--primary">Create</span><span class="df-btn df-btn--ghost">Cancel</span><i class="df-dot" style="position:static;">3</i></div>
                </div>
            </DashFrame>
            <ChatMock
                title="#your_channel"
                caption="Thirty seconds later, in chat."
                lines={[
                    { who: 'viewer', name: 'maya_live', text: '!discord' },
                    { who: 'bot', text: 'Come hang out between streams → discord.gg/your-invite' },
                ]}
            />
            <p>
                The editor also offers access levels (everyone → broadcaster), a cooldown, and a
                "only while live" switch, all optional, all explained in the
                <a href="/guides/commands">commands guide</a>.
            </p>
        </Fragment>

        <Fragment slot="first-module">
            <p>
                Head to <strong>Modules</strong>. Each tile is one feature with its own switch, and
                clicking a tile opens its settings. Two are already working for you out of the box:
                <strong>Chat Alerts</strong> (follows, subs, cheers, raids) and <strong>AutoMod</strong>
                (the layered moderation you read about on the homepage).
            </p>
            <DashFrame
                path="/modules"
                caption="The modules grid. Flip a switch, click a tile to make it yours."
                notes={[
                    { n: 1, text: 'Already on: alerts thank followers and subs with a message you can rewrite.' },
                    { n: 2, text: "Opt-in: timers post a message on a schedule while you're live. Great for the Discord plug." },
                ]}
            >
                <div class="df-main">
                    <p class="df-title">Modules</p>
                    <div class="df-grid">
                        <div class="df-tile"><b>Chat Alerts</b><small>Follow, sub, cheer & raid messages</small><span class="df-toggle is-on"></span><i class="df-dot" style="top:10px; right:10px;">1</i></div>
                        <div class="df-tile"><b>AutoMod</b><small>Layered chat moderation</small><span class="df-toggle is-on"></span></div>
                        <div class="df-tile"><b>Timers</b><small>Scheduled messages while live</small><span class="df-toggle"></span><i class="df-dot" style="top:10px; right:10px;">2</i></div>
                        <div class="df-tile"><b>Loyalty Points</b><small>Watch-time points & counters</small><span class="df-toggle"></span></div>
                        <div class="df-tile"><b>Auto Shoutout</b><small>Greets incoming raids</small><span class="df-toggle"></span></div>
                        <div class="df-tile"><b>Bedwars Stats</b><small>Hypixel stats in chat</small><span class="df-toggle"></span></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </DashFrame>
            <p>
                Nothing here is dangerous to poke: every module can be switched off as quickly as it
                came on, and its settings are kept for the next time. The full tour of what each one
                does lives in the <a href="/guides/modules">modules handbook</a>.
            </p>
        </Fragment>

        <Fragment slot="go-live">
            <p>Before your next stream, a quick rehearsal:</p>
            <ol>
                <li>Type your new command in chat yourself: the bot answers you like any viewer.</li>
                <li>Skim the <strong>Chat Alerts</strong> messages and make them sound like you.</li>
                <li>Raided often? Switch on <strong>Auto Shoutout</strong> so incoming raiders get greeted even when you're mid-game.</li>
            </ol>
            <p>
                That's the whole setup. The bot moderates, greets, and answers on its own from here,
                and everything you just did can be changed mid-stream from your phone.
            </p>
            <p class="gtip">
                <b>Next up</b>
                Make your commands smart: <a href="/guides/commands">Commands &amp; variables</a> shows
                how one line like <code>Welcome, &lbrace;user&rbrace;!</code> greets every viewer by name.
            </p>
        </Fragment>
    </GuideShell>
</Layout>
